{
  "schema_version": "1.0",
  "id": "form32",
  "kind": "curve",
  "meta": {
    "title": "MESS Prognostic Index — risk of seizure recurrence (Part 2)",
    "doi": "10.1016/S1474-4422(06)70383-0",
    "cff_info": "<h3>MESS Prognostic Index (Part 2)</h3>\n<p>Estimates the likelihood of seizure recurrence and guides treatment decisions after a single seizure or early epilepsy diagnosis. Derived from the MRC Multicentre Trial for Early Epilepsy and Single Seizures (MESS), it categorises patients into six groups by risk level (low, medium, high) and treatment timing (immediate or delayed).</p>\n<h3>Variables</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Number of seizures before presentation</strong> &mdash; one (low baseline), two to three (moderate increase), or four or more (high).</li>\n<li><strong>EEG results</strong> &mdash; a normal EEG lowers the risk profile; an abnormal (epileptiform or slow-wave) EEG significantly increases it.</li>\n<li><strong>Neurological disorder or deficit</strong> (impairment, learning disability, developmental delay) &mdash; raises recurrence risk.</li>\n<li><strong>Treatment timing</strong> &mdash; immediate treatment reduces recurrence risk in medium- and high-risk groups in the initial years; delayed treatment allows natural progression and is reasonable for low-risk patients where the benefit of early treatment is minimal.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Risk classification (prognostic index, 0&ndash;4 points)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Low (0 points)</strong> &mdash; single seizure, normal EEG, no neurological disorder.</li>\n<li><strong>Intermediate (1 point)</strong> &mdash; two to three seizures, or a single seizure with either an abnormal EEG or a neurological disorder.</li>\n<li><strong>High (2&ndash;4 points)</strong> &mdash; four or more seizures, or a combination of abnormal EEG and neurological disorder.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Part 1 of the MESS tool (risk of recurrence after a first seizure, with COSY for driving) is provided as a separate calculator.</em></p>",
    "authors": "Kim LG, Johnson TL, Marson AG, et al.",
    "journal": "The Lancet Neurology",
    "year": 2006,
    "outcome": "Prediction of risk of seizure recurrence after a single seizure and early epilepsy: further results from the MESS trial"
  },
  "thresholds": {
    "group1": 20,
    "group2": 2
  },
  "predictors": [
    {
      "name": "Treatment Type",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "Immediate",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Delayed",
          "points": 100
        }
      ],
      "assess": "Immediate vs delayed (deferred) antiepileptic-drug treatment after the first seizure, as randomised in MESS."
    },
    {
      "name": "Number of seizures before presentation",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "One seizure",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Two or three seizures",
          "points": 1
        },
        {
          "label": "Four or more seizures",
          "points": 2
        }
      ],
      "assess": "Select 'Yes' if seizures occurred exclusively during sleep; otherwise, choose 'No'."
    },
    {
      "name": "EEG Results",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "Normal",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Not done",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Abnormal",
          "points": 1
        }
      ],
      "assess": "EEG results indicate brain activity patterns. Select 'Normal' if no epileptiform activity was detected. Choose 'Abnormal' if the EEG showed epileptiform activity, including focal or generalized spikes or spike-and-slow-wave patterns. Select 'Not Done' if the EEG test was not conducted."
    },
    {
      "name": "Neurological disorder or deficit, learning disability, or developmental delay",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "No",
          "points": 0
        },
        {
          "label": "Yes",
          "points": 1
        }
      ],
      "assess": "In the MESS study, Neurological Disorders are defined as including: Neurological Deficits: Conditions such as motor impairments or sensory losses caused by prior brain injury or disease. Learning Disabilities: Cognitive impairments impacting the ability to acquire knowledge or skills. Developmental Delays: Delays in reaching age-appropriate milestones in physical, cognitive, or social domains. These factors are associated with a higher likelihood of seizure recurrence and are used in the calculation of the risk index."
    }
  ],
